Of. 13, supra—The speech of A. is not equal to that of Galgacus. He had not so good a cause. He could not appeal to the sacred principles of justice and liberty, to the love of home and household gods. But he makes the best of a. bad cause. The speech is worthy of a. Roman commender, and touches with masterly skill all those chords in a Roman soldier's breast, that were never touched in vain.
